# Keep navigation in sync across every page

This is a static HTML/CSS site with **no build step and no shared-include mechanism**.
The nav/sidebar (list of pages), the hamburger menu, and the footer are physically
**copied into every HTML page**. There is no single source of truth to edit.

## The invariant

Whenever the set of pages changes, the navigation in **every** HTML page must be updated
to match. Treat the nav/sidebar markup as one logical block that happens to be duplicated.

## Triggers — when this applies

- **Adding a page** → add its link to the nav/sidebar in *every other* page (and the new page).
- **Removing a page** → delete its link from the nav/sidebar in *every* page.
- **Renaming a page** (title or URL/slug) → update the link text and/or `href` in *every* page.
- **Reordering nav items** → apply the same order in *every* page.

## Link format (extensionless)

Internal links are **relative and extensionless** so they work on GitHub Pages
(which resolves `/biking` to `biking.html`) on both a custom domain and a project
path. Use `href="biking"`, not `href="biking.html"`. The Home link is `href="./"`.

## How to do it correctly

1. Enumerate all HTML pages (e.g. `**/*.html`) so none are missed.
2. Apply the identical nav/sidebar/footer change to each one.
3. After editing, grep for the added/removed/renamed link text and `href` across all
   pages to confirm every page has the exact same nav block. Also confirm no
   `.html"` sneaks back into an internal `href`.
4. Don't hand-wave "and the others" — actually edit each file.
